actually moving is orbit

00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:24.490
and precisely parallels the boy
whirling the stone around its head,

00:29:24.490 --> 00:29:27.050
it's a stone here it's
no longer an apple.

00:29:27.050 --> 00:29:29.790
And both of them explain
the combination

00:29:29.790 --> 00:29:32.890
between centrifugal
forces and gravitation

00:29:32.890 --> 00:29:36.520
which keeps the earth
orbiting the sun.

00:29:36.520 --> 00:29:40.850 position:56%
Maurice Allward's book was published
after satellites had been launched

00:29:40.850 --> 00:29:44.340 position:56%
into earth's orbit and thus explains
the interplay between centrifugal

00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:46.740
and gravitational force
in term of the earth

00:29:46.740 --> 00:29:48.710
and its satellites instead.

00:29:48.710 --> 00:29:51.450
And the parallel is again made
explicit by the two drawings

00:29:51.450 --> 00:29:54.860
on the right-hand side
displaying significant parallel

00:29:54.860 --> 00:29:56.600
compositional aspects.

00:29:56.600 --> 00:29:59.860
The location of the boy's had
parallel that of the earth right,

00:29:59.860 --> 00:30:03.040
they're on the same place in
the picture and the conqueror.

00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:06.090
This boy is not using an apple or
a stone, but he has a conqueror,

00:30:06.090 --> 00:30:08.070
the conqueror is almost
in the same place

00:30:08.070 --> 00:30:10.560
as the satellite is going
around in the orbit.

00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:13.230
So again, you can see
the parallel compositions

00:30:13.230 --> 00:30:15.530
between the two pictures.

00:30:17.140 --> 00:30:20.740
So one parallel, but back
to Peter Parley for now.

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:23.740
The next illustration
show how Goodrich explains

00:30:23.740 --> 00:30:26.900
that the earth turns around the sun
rather than the other way around

00:30:26.900 --> 00:30:31.700
and that the sun always shines
on some part of the earth.

00:30:31.700 --> 00:30:36.600
And so on the left you
can see someone reaching

00:30:36.600 --> 00:30:39.240
out behind the curtain holding
an apple, so that's an apple

00:30:39.240 --> 00:30:42.000
on a string that he's
holding next to the candle.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:46.270
And the other one has the
sun shining on the earth.

00:30:46.270 --> 00:30:48.890
So if you turn the
apple that you have

00:30:48.890 --> 00:30:52.060
on the little string the
candle shines on its other side

00:30:52.060 --> 00:30:55.250
and while your side might turn
dark the candle keeps shining

00:30:55.250 --> 00:30:56.840
on the apple all the same.

00:30:56.840 --> 00:30:59.670
This illustration also
introduces one of the problems

00:30:59.670 --> 00:31:03.650
that children's book illustrators
often contended with and especially

00:31:03.650 --> 00:31:08.660
in more recent -- no not so recent
book, where to put the clouds,

00:31:08.660 --> 00:31:10.620
where do you put the clouds right.

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:14.080
When you look up at the sky you
see clouds, but when you look

00:31:14.080 --> 00:31:17.570 position:56%
at the earth from space do you see
clouds or do you not see the clouds?

00:31:17.570 --> 00:31:21.000
And if we've talked about
my project at any length

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:25.210
in time I've probably joked to
you that before 1946 the weather

00:31:25.210 --> 00:31:27.840 position:56%
on the earth was much better
because there were never any clouds,

00:31:27.840 --> 00:31:31.600
there are never any clouds
from space very rarely.

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:33.550
Interestingly, this
is not quite true

00:31:33.550 --> 00:31:35.320
for this Peter Parley illustration.

00:31:35.320 --> 00:31:38.820 position:56%
Here the artist clearly knew that he
had to include the clouds somewhere,

00:31:38.820 --> 00:31:41.300
but at the same time if you
don't want to obscure the view

00:31:41.300 --> 00:31:43.670
of the earth and paint
them on the earth

00:31:43.670 --> 00:31:46.810
and then the people can recognize
the earth where would you put them?

00:31:46.810 --> 00:31:50.770 position:56%
So here his solution was to put them
around the sun, which technically

00:31:50.770 --> 00:31:52.990
from the point of view of
someone standing on the earth

00:31:52.990 --> 00:31:55.060
and looking up is kind of true.

00:31:55.060 --> 00:31:57.850
But also of course,
not actually the case,

00:31:57.850 --> 00:32:02.010
so keep in mind where
the clouds are.

00:32:02.010 --> 00:32:05.270 position:56%
And last but not least, there's also
this interesting view of the earth

00:32:05.270 --> 00:32:08.930
in the book, which really seems

00:32:08.930 --> 00:32:12.420
to be planet water
rather than planet earth.

00:32:12.420 --> 00:32:14.440
So we're going to zoom in a little.

00:32:14.440 --> 00:32:16.910
The quality of my image
is not the best,

00:32:16.910 --> 00:32:21.260
but you can see this is water world
more than it is anything else.

00:32:21.260 --> 00:32:23.300
The book does not give
any explanation

00:32:23.300 --> 00:32:26.310
for this it just has a ton
of ships on this planet

00:32:26.310 --> 00:32:30.770
and no continents,
which is interesting.

00:32:30.770 --> 00:32:33.840
And another interesting image
I'm going to show you is

00:32:33.840 --> 00:32:38.980
from Samuel Goodrich's 1846
National Geography for schools,

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:42.250
so this is the front page.

00:32:42.250 --> 00:32:44.710
And there again, we see
the clouds around the earth

00:32:44.710 --> 00:32:46.780
and the earth looks like this.

00:32:46.780 --> 00:32:48.080
Is there anything that
might be missing?

00:32:58.040 --> 00:33:02.930
Asia yes, so the visible part
of the earth is only North

00:33:02.930 --> 00:33:06.850
and South America, nothing else,
but he included the clouds.

00:33:06.850 --> 00:33:10.370
So something of this and
a little less if that.

00:33:10.370 --> 00:33:13.190
So now you've seen
Goodrich's problem of where

00:33:13.190 --> 00:33:16.110
to locate the clouds and
also some images of the earth

00:33:16.110 --> 00:33:20.690
without any clouds actually
between you and viewing it.

00:33:20.690 --> 00:33:23.170
And let me show you how
the planet earth and clouds

00:33:23.170 --> 00:33:27.740
on the earth's surface are depicted
in the intervening 180 years.

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:36.570
So these three, I hope you can
see these okay even from the back.

00:33:36.570 --> 00:33:41.280
These are from John
Astor, yes the John Astor.

00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:45.710
A Journey in Other Worlds and
Romans of the Future from 1894,

00:33:45.710 --> 00:33:49.660
Mary Proctor's The Children's
Book of the Heavens from 1928

00:33:49.660 --> 00:33:54.730
and the Stars for Sam
from W. M. Reed from 1931.

00:33:54.730 --> 00:33:58.090
And here you can actually
see some clouds if you look

00:33:58.090 --> 00:34:01.250
at the Astor picture,
which is the big one.

00:34:01.250 --> 00:34:04.310
The description says the signal
is from the Arctic Circle.

00:34:04.310 --> 00:34:06.510
So they need to find out
where they're going to land

00:34:06.510 --> 00:34:08.250 position:56%
and the signal helps them with that.

00:34:08.250 --> 00:34:11.780
But you can actually see
South America and some clouds

00:34:11.780 --> 00:34:15.980
around it whereas in the other two
books -- Proctor still has some,

00:34:15.980 --> 00:34:19.620
but then in W. M. Reed's
book it's the first book

00:34:19.620 --> 00:34:21.420
where we're starting
to lose the clouds.

00:34:21.420 --> 00:34:25.260
So we have clouds and then we
start kind of losing more clouds

00:34:25.260 --> 00:34:28.290
and we will not see
any clouds for a while.

00:34:28.290 --> 00:34:33.420 position:56%
So these are the next
illustrations -- that these are all,

00:34:33.420 --> 00:34:37.130
these are from between
1935 and 1945 and that's

00:34:37.130 --> 00:34:40.680
when we really start seeing lots of
books about space expiration again.

00:34:40.680 --> 00:34:43.940
In the decades before that they
are few and far between either

00:34:43.940 --> 00:34:46.050
in fiction or they're
astronomy books.

00:34:46.050 --> 00:34:49.950
And it took me two weeks to figure
out why that is, why do people talk

00:34:49.950 --> 00:34:53.580
about space a lot like
in the 1840's, 50's,

00:34:53.580 --> 00:34:56.180
60's, 70's and then they stop.

00:34:56.180 --> 00:35:00.340 position:56%
It's because people start building
planes and all the [inaudible] books

00:35:00.340 --> 00:35:03.670
of wonder are about aviation
and not about the stars anymore.

00:35:03.670 --> 00:35:05.470
I felt very stupid once
I figured that out.

00:35:05.470 --> 00:35:06.870
I thought of course, of course,

00:35:06.870 --> 00:35:09.560
that's when we started having
aircraft and everyone's about hey,

00:35:09.560 --> 00:35:12.460
we're going to fly the Pole
[inaudible] fly into space.

00:35:12.460 --> 00:35:13.940
But space comes back.

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:21.110
So here as I said, these are from
W. B. White I'm Seeing Stars 1935,

00:35:21.110 --> 00:35:26.500
Arthur Draper's Wonders
of the Heavens from 1940,

00:35:26.500 --> 00:35:29.930 position:56%
Bertha M. Parker the Earth's Nearest
neighbor, which is the big picture

00:35:29.930 --> 00:35:33.260
and then the Picture Book of
Astronomy by Jerome S. Meyer,

00:35:33.260 --> 00:35:35.080
which we will keep
coming back to today

00:35:35.080 --> 00:35:36.780
which is the bottom left picture.

00:35:36.780 --> 00:35:38.300
And here what is significant is

00:35:38.300 --> 00:35:41.680
that the earth pretty much
look like a glow from space.

00:35:41.680 --> 00:35:45.970
So there's an absence of the
clouds, we see very clearly North

00:35:45.970 --> 00:35:49.450
and South America and inn American
children's books it's always North

00:35:49.450 --> 00:35:51.280
and South America that you see.

00:35:51.280 --> 00:35:54.350
In Russian children's books it's
not Russia interestingly enough,

00:35:54.350 --> 00:35:57.510
they often show like in
the North Pole or parts

00:35:57.510 --> 00:36:02.850 position:56%
of Europe they don't focus to such
a degree on the US and South America

00:36:02.850 --> 00:36:04.850
as American children's books do.

00:36:04.850 --> 00:36:07.990
So now we're in 1945 there are
no clouds on the planet earth,

00:36:07.990 --> 00:36:10.860
everything is sunny everywhere,
the weather is always good

00:36:10.860 --> 00:36:14.710
and then silence has to
come in and ruin the view.

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:17.790
So it's 1946 and this happens.

00:36:17.790 --> 00:36:21.950
This is the first photograph of
the earth in which you see clouds

00:36:21.950 --> 00:36:24.940
from above and it was
taken on October 24th,

00:36:24.940 --> 00:36:28.560
1946 and it's the first
photograph from space.

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:32.360
It was taken from a V2 rocket
launched in the New Mexico desert

00:36:32.360 --> 00:36:35.680
and which had been fitted with a
35 millimeter motion picture camera

00:36:35.680 --> 00:36:41.530 position:56%
and went up to a suborbital altitude
of 105 kilometers or 65 miles

00:36:41.530 --> 00:36:43.890
as I should probably say here.

00:36:43.890 --> 00:36:46.080
The camera was destroyed
after being dropped back

00:36:46.080 --> 00:36:48.320 position:56%
to the earth, but the film survived.

00:36:48.320 --> 00:36:52.220 position:56%
You can see it here at the top left,
along with an image of the page

00:36:52.220 --> 00:36:53.880
from the Christian Science Monitor,

00:36:53.880 --> 00:36:56.090
which talks about it
which is on the right.

00:36:56.090 --> 00:36:58.540
And here courtesy of the
Microphone Collection

00:36:58.540 --> 00:37:00.650
in the Newspaper Reading Room.

00:37:00.650 --> 00:37:03.070
I'm showing you this page
here alongside the photograph

00:37:03.070 --> 00:37:04.740
so you can get a feeling
for the fact

00:37:04.740 --> 00:37:06.650
that these images were
widely circulated

00:37:06.650 --> 00:37:09.090
in the press, which
indeed they were.

00:37:09.090 --> 00:37:12.640
And another highly influential
publication this time not a

00:37:12.640 --> 00:37:16.580
photograph, but a magazine
article or rather a series

00:37:16.580 --> 00:37:20.720
of magazine articles was
published in Colliers between 1952

00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:24.210
and 1954 and that's this one.

00:37:24.210 --> 00:37:26.550
And these are some of the
most influential drawings

00:37:26.550 --> 00:37:28.980
of the planet earth
ever, ever, ever,

00:37:28.980 --> 00:37:32.650
ever and especially
of space stations.

00:37:32.650 --> 00:37:36.860
They inspired a great deal of
children's books' illustrators

00:37:36.860 --> 00:37:40.150
and Colliers ran a series of
articles on humankind's future

00:37:40.150 --> 00:37:44.340 position:56%
in space in which leading scientists
talk about space exploration.

00:37:44.340 --> 00:37:48.860 position:56%
And these illustrations here were
taken from the first of these issues

00:37:48.860 --> 00:37:52.980
of Colliers and this one was
called Man Will Conquer Space Soon.

00:37:52.980 --> 00:37:57.320
The article is drawn by Chesley
Bonestell, one of the pioneers

00:37:57.320 --> 00:38:00.280
of space art who greatly
helped popularize space travel

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:04.880
and whose illustrations have
become so iconic that people refer

00:38:04.880 --> 00:38:07.270
to other artists as
either being Bonestallion

00:38:07.270 --> 00:38:10.100
or not quite Bonestallion enough.

00:38:10.100 --> 00:38:13.430
Here he is illustrating an article
written by [inaudible] Brown

00:38:13.430 --> 00:38:18.300
about space stations and crossing
the last frontier into space.

00:38:18.300 --> 00:38:21.500
And if you keep this picture in
mind and then look at the next one

00:38:21.500 --> 00:38:25.560
so you can see what I mean about
them being very influential.

00:38:25.560 --> 00:38:32.530
So especially the two on the right
they seem almost identical right,

00:38:32.530 --> 00:38:36.970
it's a different artist but
clearly copies the style.

00:38:36.970 --> 00:38:41.150
These are from Arthur C. Clarke's
Exploration of the Moon in 1954,

00:38:41.150 --> 00:38:44.340
illustrated by Ralph
Smith and then Rose Wyler

00:38:44.340 --> 00:38:47.450
and Gerald Ames' Golden Book of
Astronomy, a Child's Introduction

00:38:47.450 --> 00:38:51.380
to the Wonders of Space, and Willy
Levy Man-Made Satellites Adventure

00:38:51.380 --> 00:38:54.030
in Space from 1955 and 57.

00:38:54.030 --> 00:38:56.530
And both of these were
illustrated by John Paul Green,

00:38:56.530 --> 00:38:59.610
so that's why the images look
so similar it's the same artist

00:38:59.610 --> 00:39:03.360
who clearly was influenced
by Chesley Bonestell.

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:07.260
The earth looks a bit scary here,
there's not a hole being dug

00:39:07.260 --> 00:39:10.570
in the earth so the earth is not
slowly disintegrating into itself.

00:39:10.570 --> 00:39:13.800
The book is illustrating
an eclipse of the moon what

00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:16.440
that would look like from space.

00:39:16.440 --> 00:39:19.080
So the moon's shadow
is on the earth here,

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:22.380
that's why it has that dark spot.

00:39:22.380 --> 00:39:25.770
The next photograph that
is very influential or no,

00:39:25.770 --> 00:39:31.830
the next autograph is from 1959
and shows the first photograph

00:39:31.830 --> 00:39:35.410 position:56%
of the earth taken from a satellite,
namely by the Explorer 6 Satellite

00:39:35.410 --> 00:39:38.600
on the 14th of August
1959 from a height

00:39:38.600 --> 00:39:42.390
of about 27,000 kilometers
or 70,000 miles.

00:39:42.390 --> 00:39:43.770
The [inaudible], that's the one

00:39:43.770 --> 00:39:46.220
on the top left it clearly
shows a sunlighted area

00:39:46.220 --> 00:39:50.810
of the central Pacific Ocean
and its cloud cover right.

00:39:50.810 --> 00:39:54.760 position:56%
Of much better quality was the first
television picture from space sent

00:39:54.760 --> 00:39:58.090
to earth on April 1st,
1960 and taken by TIROS-1,

00:39:58.090 --> 00:40:01.160
the first successful lower
earth orbital weather satellite.

00:40:01.160 --> 00:40:02.460
In the first of its years

00:40:02.460 --> 00:40:04.570
of television infrared
observations satellites,

00:40:04.570 --> 00:40:06.290
which is the picture
at the bottom left.

00:40:06.290 --> 00:40:10.150
And it shows the coast of Maine
and Canada's Maritime Provinces

00:40:10.150 --> 00:40:14.250
and this is when you really start
seeing the curvature of the earth

00:40:14.250 --> 00:40:16.910
and to a greater degree and
cloud cover of the earth.

00:40:16.910 --> 00:40:19.920
And you start actually using
and television pictures to talk

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:23.010
about the weather and suddenly
people know what clouds look

00:40:23.010 --> 00:40:25.130
like from space to
a far greater degree

00:40:25.130 --> 00:40:26.660
than they did before even there,

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:28.330
though there they already
know it for [inaudible].

00:40:28.330 --> 00:40:33.970
And next then and this is what
really, really kicks it all off.

00:40:33.970 --> 00:40:37.590
It's time for humans to get
in on the photography action.

00:40:37.590 --> 00:40:40.780
Yuri Gagarin became the first
man in space on April 12,

00:40:40.780 --> 00:40:46.220
1961 and in February 1962 John
Glenn, the third American in space

00:40:46.220 --> 00:40:48.650
and took his camera along
with him and brought back,

00:40:48.650 --> 00:40:51.000
among others the photograph
of the earth

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:52.950 position:56%
that you see on the right-hand side.

00:40:52.950 --> 00:40:57.010
And this is when you start having
pictures taken by humans from space

00:40:57.010 --> 00:40:59.780
who then can talk about what
they saw, what it felt like to be

00:40:59.780 --> 00:41:04.490
in space, and that adds an entirely
different dimension to the way

00:41:04.490 --> 00:41:08.490 position:56%
that people draw the earth and talk
about the earth in children's books.

00:41:08.490 --> 00:41:11.760
And again, here are four
illustrations that sort

00:41:11.760 --> 00:41:13.780
of parallel this cloud cover.

00:41:13.780 --> 00:41:16.230
Some of them are more
realistic and some less,

00:41:16.230 --> 00:41:18.380
but there's also some
time in between.

00:41:18.380 --> 00:41:21.980
So the one where it's still very
sunny except for this tiny piece

00:41:21.980 --> 00:41:27.410
of cloud out in the Pacific Ocean
close to Mexico is from 1958.

00:41:27.410 --> 00:41:29.810
And then the one on the right
where the clouds are sort

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:33.610
of forming a little band around
the earth, I loved that image

00:41:33.610 --> 00:41:38.300
when I saw it, that's from the
Sun, the Moon and Stars from 1959.

00:41:38.300 --> 00:41:42.690
And then the bottom two ones are,
the bottom right one is from 1961

00:41:42.690 --> 00:41:45.570
and the one on the
bottom left is from 1963.

00:41:45.570 --> 00:41:48.350
And that one talks about
the first astronauts

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:53.150
in space while showing the
earth with a big cloud cover.

00:41:53.150 --> 00:41:57.900
So again, in the bottom right you
can clearly see there are more

00:41:57.900 --> 00:42:00.160
and more clouds being
drawn around the earth

00:42:00.160 --> 00:42:03.570
as we have the photographs, so
I'm going to skip back here?

00:42:03.570 --> 00:42:06.600
Look at the top right
photograph and then compare it

00:42:06.600 --> 00:42:08.320
to the bottom right picture right.

00:42:08.320 --> 00:42:14.190
So but maybe the most
influential single photo --

00:42:14.190 --> 00:42:19.370 position:56%
series of photographs for children's
books is actually of the spacewalk.

00:42:19.370 --> 00:42:23.630
So the photograph on the top left
here shows Ed White's spacewalk

00:42:23.630 --> 00:42:27.110
on the Gemini 4 mission
in June 1965.

00:42:27.110 --> 00:42:30.780
And this is copied widely
in children's books.

00:42:30.780 --> 00:42:33.290
So either they use the
photographs themselves,

00:42:33.290 --> 00:42:37.230
as in the top right The World of
Rockets by Alexander [inaudible]

00:42:37.230 --> 00:42:42.400
or in the bottom two pictures
where the photograph inspires art.

00:42:42.400 --> 00:42:46.160
Before that the depiction
of astronauts is kind of all

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:48.590
over the place people don't quite
know what the spacesuits are going

00:42:48.590 --> 00:42:50.980 position:56%
to look like, they have huge
antennas sticking out of their head.

00:42:50.980 --> 00:42:52.940
You're going to see one
of those pictures later.

00:42:52.940 --> 00:42:57.670
But after this spacewalks look
like Ed White's spacewalk.

00:42:57.670 --> 00:43:05.520
The next important images
from November 10th, 1967,

00:43:05.520 --> 00:43:07.870
and offers the first full
view of the planet earth

00:43:07.870 --> 00:43:10.560
that the public actually
gets to see.

00:43:10.560 --> 00:43:14.070
There is most likely arguably
an earlier photograph taken

00:43:14.070 --> 00:43:17.640
by a military dodge satellite which
was never released to the public.

00:43:17.640 --> 00:43:20.550
And so while interesting it's
not interesting to my project

00:43:20.550 --> 00:43:24.300
because it's never released it
cannot inspire anyone all right.

00:43:24.300 --> 00:43:28.410
And like the photo that I will
talk about after this one,

00:43:28.410 --> 00:43:32.310
this photograph has been largely
overshadowed in collective memory

00:43:32.310 --> 00:43:36.660
since in its case by Apollo 17's
famous blue marble photograph.

00:43:36.660 --> 00:43:38.680
So if I ask you what
was the first photograph

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:41.460
of the completely illuminated
glow from space,

00:43:41.460 --> 00:43:43.210
most people would say
the blue marble.

00:43:43.210 --> 00:43:45.730
And it wasn't actually
it was this one,

00:43:45.730 --> 00:43:49.470
which was taken five years
earlier than the blue marble.

00:43:49.470 --> 00:43:52.940 position:56%
But when this photograph here was
taken it was a huge deal at the time

00:43:52.940 --> 00:43:56.410
in children's books and it was
very quickly adapted into them.

00:43:56.410 --> 00:43:59.150
So it was released, it caused
huge excitement for the public

00:43:59.150 --> 00:44:03.450
and it was very quickly covered
and put into children's books.

00:44:03.450 --> 00:44:06.920
So at the top right this
book is called Exploring

