they don't do illustrations so
much anymore they use photographs

00:44:52.120 --> 00:44:55.560
because we have so
many great photographs.

00:44:55.560 --> 00:44:59.000
So photography wise it is 1967 now

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:03.520
and thus the year before Apollo
8 goes to the moon and that is

00:45:03.520 --> 00:45:06.120
where we will leave
space photography for now

00:45:06.120 --> 00:45:08.990
for the relationship between the
earth and the moon is something

00:45:08.990 --> 00:45:12.390
that is also extensively covered
in children's books as well.

00:45:12.390 --> 00:45:15.320
And for which we shall once
again start in the 1840's

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:17.250
and then move away forward.

00:45:17.250 --> 00:45:24.640 position:56%
All right, there are two more books
from the 1840's that I want to delve

00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:27.980
into a little, namely J. L.
Comstock's Youth Book of Astronomy

00:45:27.980 --> 00:45:32.560
from 1835 and John Blake's
First Book in Astronomy adapted

00:45:32.560 --> 00:45:35.960
for the use of common
schools from 1936.

00:45:35.960 --> 00:45:39.580
They're both interesting because
they while not providing the reader

00:45:39.580 --> 00:45:42.980
with any detailed illustrations
of the earth itself,

00:45:42.980 --> 00:45:46.350
discuss what the earth would
look like when seen from the moon

00:45:46.350 --> 00:45:49.370
and thus highlight a very common
feature of children's books.

00:45:49.370 --> 00:45:52.370
Someone is standing on the moon
and looking back at the earth

00:45:52.370 --> 00:45:55.830
and when I say it's a very common
feature, I mean it's a very, very,

00:45:55.830 --> 00:45:57.630
very, very common feature.

00:45:57.630 --> 00:46:00.300
It's almost in every children's
books where you go into space,

00:46:00.300 --> 00:46:02.200
you stand on the moon and
you look back on the earth

00:46:02.200 --> 00:46:09.360
and you think something about the
earth and that changes over time.

00:46:09.360 --> 00:46:18.460
So Blake -- so Blake in his
First Book on Astronomy adapted

00:46:18.460 --> 00:46:22.240
for the use of common
schools writes the following,

00:46:22.240 --> 00:46:25.820
as the moon illuminates the earth
by light reflected from the sun

00:46:25.820 --> 00:46:28.430
so it is reciprocally
illuminated by the earth,

00:46:28.430 --> 00:46:32.080
which reflects the sun's rays
to the surface of the moon.

00:46:32.080 --> 00:46:35.860 position:56%
And as the surface of the earth is
more than 13 times greater than that

00:46:35.860 --> 00:46:38.720
of the moon, the earth
must appear to inhabitants

00:46:38.720 --> 00:46:42.690
of the moon 13 times larger
than the moon does to us.

00:46:42.690 --> 00:46:45.200
The rotation of the moon
and its axis being performed

00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:48.310
in the same time that it goes
around the earth it is plain

00:46:48.310 --> 00:46:52.750 position:56%
that the inhabitants of one half of
the lunar world are totally deprived

00:46:52.750 --> 00:46:57.410 position:56%
of the side of the earth unless they
travel to the opposite hemisphere.

00:46:57.410 --> 00:47:00.080
So if you live on the moon it
depends on where you live whether

00:47:00.080 --> 00:47:01.430
or not you get to see the earth.

00:47:01.430 --> 00:47:03.930
If you live on the far side
of the moon and then you go

00:47:03.930 --> 00:47:07.090
around the earth you go oh,
what is this thing right.

00:47:07.090 --> 00:47:09.330
And Comstock kind of
writes the same thing,

00:47:09.330 --> 00:47:11.680
but he does so in a far
more lyrical fashion,

00:47:11.680 --> 00:47:13.710
which is why I'm quoting it too.

00:47:13.710 --> 00:47:15.800 position:56%
We have already stated that one side

00:47:15.800 --> 00:47:18.440
of the moon is never
turned towards the earth.

00:47:18.440 --> 00:47:22.690 position:56%
Consequently, to the lunarians which
are his inhabitants of the moon,

00:47:22.690 --> 00:47:26.530
who live on the side nearest to
us the earth is always visible,

00:47:26.530 --> 00:47:28.850
except when the moon
is in opposition.

00:47:28.850 --> 00:47:31.800
But those who live on the opposite
side of the moon and always stay

00:47:31.800 --> 00:47:34.130
at home never see the earth at all

00:47:34.130 --> 00:47:36.850
because that side is
never turned towards us.

00:47:36.850 --> 00:47:41.090
A lunar astronomer who happens to
live on the side directly opposite

00:47:41.090 --> 00:47:45.410 position:56%
to us would have to travel a quarter
of the circumference of his planet

00:47:45.410 --> 00:47:49.670
to see the earth at all
that is about 1,500 miles.

00:47:49.670 --> 00:47:51.090
And if you would see our orb

00:47:51.090 --> 00:47:56.360 position:56%
in its greatest magnificence he
must go 3,000 miles or to the middle

00:47:56.360 --> 00:47:59.950
of the part next to us where
indeed he will behold a spectacle

00:47:59.950 --> 00:48:02.900
which any terrestrial
astronomer would be happy

00:48:02.900 --> 00:48:05.790
to enjoy at such an expense.

00:48:05.790 --> 00:48:09.920
Namely a moon always directly
over his head, 13 times as large

00:48:09.920 --> 00:48:13.600
as the full moon appears to
us and turning on its axis

00:48:13.600 --> 00:48:17.670
so that he could examine
every part of it in 24 hours.

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:19.910
Don't you want to live
on the moon now?

00:48:19.910 --> 00:48:25.150
So as I said, unfortunately no
detailed illustrations of the earth

00:48:25.150 --> 00:48:27.290
from space or indeed
what the earth might look

00:48:27.290 --> 00:48:30.230
like from the moon are provided
by either Blake or Comstock.

00:48:30.230 --> 00:48:35.130
The most you get is in Comstock
this drawing of an eclipse

00:48:35.130 --> 00:48:39.100
like when the moon is dark because
the earth is between the sun

00:48:39.100 --> 00:48:41.550
and the moon, that's the
most you get of the earth.

00:48:41.550 --> 00:48:46.990
And it takes almost a hundred years
until the first image of the earth

00:48:46.990 --> 00:48:50.780
as seen from the moon shows up in
children's books and it is in 1924

00:48:50.780 --> 00:48:52.840 position:56%
in May Proctor's The Children's Book

00:48:52.840 --> 00:48:56.550
of the Heavens and
it looks like this.

00:48:56.550 --> 00:49:00.020
This is a typical image for the
1920's, so it takes a while to show

00:49:00.020 --> 00:49:03.380
up and then these are the
kind of images you get.

00:49:03.380 --> 00:49:07.040
And the best one in
color that I have found,

00:49:07.040 --> 00:49:10.270
which is why I'm showing
it to you here.

00:49:10.270 --> 00:49:12.330
The moon as we all
know from seeing it

00:49:12.330 --> 00:49:15.220
at night shines bright
yellow in the earth's sky.

00:49:15.220 --> 00:49:17.090
And so for a long time
it seemed to follow

00:49:17.090 --> 00:49:19.530
that the earth too would be
bright yellow when we looked at it

00:49:19.530 --> 00:49:22.070
from the moon right, one is
yellow the other one is yellow

00:49:22.070 --> 00:49:23.620
seems logical.

00:49:23.620 --> 00:49:26.120
This one is actually
slightly atypical

00:49:26.120 --> 00:49:29.190
in that it does not show some
detail in the earth's surface,

00:49:29.190 --> 00:49:34.790 position:56%
even if the planet as a whole seems
more reminiscent of drawings of Mars

00:49:34.790 --> 00:49:37.250
and the canals that
might exist on Mars

00:49:37.250 --> 00:49:38.640
that were also frequent subjects

00:49:38.640 --> 00:49:40.950
in children's astronomy
books of the time right.

00:49:40.950 --> 00:49:44.750 position:56%
If I said you what is this you'd
say oh is this Mars, it's the earth.

00:49:44.750 --> 00:49:49.000
And the description says the earth
seen from the moon's [inaudible].

00:49:58.070 --> 00:50:03.250
So details start showing up in the
1930's and these three images are

00:50:03.250 --> 00:50:06.010 position:56%
from left to right from Elena Fontay

00:50:06.010 --> 00:50:10.490
of the world's [inaudible]
from 1930.

00:50:10.490 --> 00:50:12.160
Otto Gail's By Rocket to the Moon,

00:50:12.160 --> 00:50:15.900
the story of Hans Hardt's
Miraculous flight from 1931.

00:50:15.900 --> 00:50:20.850
And W. M. Reed's The Stars
for Sam in 1931 as well.

00:50:20.850 --> 00:50:26.960
So interestingly, the continents
here are only vaguely determinable

00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:28.790
and clouds too seem
to actually exist

00:50:28.790 --> 00:50:30.860
and obscure the features
of the earth.

00:50:30.860 --> 00:50:32.580
So again, it's a parallel

00:50:32.580 --> 00:50:34.180
to the earlier pictures
we had of the earth.

00:50:34.180 --> 00:50:38.360
In the 1930's you have clouds, in
the 1940's there are no clouds.

00:50:38.360 --> 00:50:41.940
And maybe unsurprisingly if you
look at the earth from the moon

00:50:41.940 --> 00:50:44.770
in the 1940's there are no clouds.

00:50:44.770 --> 00:50:50.630
So we're going back to Bertha M.
Parker The Earth's Nearest Neighbor

00:50:50.630 --> 00:50:54.050
and then Jeremy S. Meyers,
the Picture Book of Astronomy

00:50:54.050 --> 00:50:58.910
and on the far right Marion
Cothren's 1946 This is the Moon,

00:50:58.910 --> 00:51:03.780
which sort of has the earth
rising behind the moon.

00:51:03.780 --> 00:51:06.540
And this way of drawing the
earth doesn't really change

00:51:06.540 --> 00:51:10.050
until the late 1950's and clouds
start appearing in these drawings

00:51:10.050 --> 00:51:11.540
of the earth as seen from the moon.

00:51:11.540 --> 00:51:15.510
So it really takes us after the
first satellites are in space,

00:51:15.510 --> 00:51:19.900 position:56%
but before manned spaceflight begins
for these pictures of the earth

00:51:19.900 --> 00:51:23.720
to change a little as they
are seen from the moon.

00:51:23.720 --> 00:51:26.120
And then you get pictures
like these and all four

00:51:26.120 --> 00:51:29.490
of these are primarily concerned
with our future in space

00:51:29.490 --> 00:51:32.650
and exploring the moon so you
can see various iterations

00:51:32.650 --> 00:51:35.950
of rocket ships going
there or unmanned probes

00:51:35.950 --> 00:51:38.060
that might land on the moon.

00:51:38.060 --> 00:51:40.680
And you also always
see the earth somewhere

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:42.220
in the lunar sky, that's
very common.

00:51:42.220 --> 00:51:45.870
If you draw people landing on
the moon and working on the moon

00:51:45.870 --> 00:51:49.040
and you always include the earth
somewhere to show that they are

00:51:49.040 --> 00:51:50.850
on the moon and not
on some random plant

00:51:50.850 --> 00:51:53.370
and because it's a
nice visual sight.

00:51:57.600 --> 00:52:02.080
So where am I, I adlibbed.

00:52:02.080 --> 00:52:04.840
Photographs of the earth as seen
from lunar orbit are something

00:52:04.840 --> 00:52:07.730
that once they are available
are also quickly integrated

00:52:07.730 --> 00:52:11.420
into children's books as well,
somewhat unsurprisingly probably.

00:52:11.420 --> 00:52:14.370
Maybe even more so by sheer
amount than the early photographs

00:52:14.370 --> 00:52:16.410
of the earth from orbit
actually are,

00:52:16.410 --> 00:52:21.040 position:56%
