rather than being copied one-on-one.

00:52:21.040 --> 00:52:24.190
The first photograph of the earth
from lunar orbit, which was taken

00:52:24.190 --> 00:52:28.000
in 1966 by the lunar orbiter
this very quickly turns

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.880
up in front papers and end
papers of children's books,

00:52:30.880 --> 00:52:33.660
as well as integrated
into the text itself.

00:52:33.660 --> 00:52:36.660
Today again, few people might
recall that this image existed

00:52:36.660 --> 00:52:41.130
as it has been overshadowed by the
Apollo 8 and Earthrise photograph,

00:52:41.130 --> 00:52:44.210
which we saw earlier
but it did exist.

00:52:44.210 --> 00:52:47.750
And interesting about this picture
is that while it is integrated

00:52:47.750 --> 00:52:50.510
into the text sometimes it
also shows up in the front

00:52:50.510 --> 00:52:53.250
and in the end papers, even if the
book doesn't really talk about it.

00:52:53.250 --> 00:52:55.460
It's just there because it
exists and you want to show it

00:52:55.460 --> 00:52:58.220
to the children, that's my theory.

00:52:58.220 --> 00:53:01.950 position:56%
It's like it doesn't really fit in
